Wine Quality Prediction¶

About Data

  • The dataset consists of two subsets, red and white variants of the Portuguese "Vinho Verde" wine. The dataset contains only physicochemical (inputs) and sensory (output) variables, and no data on grape types, wine brand, or selling price.
  • The goal of the dataset is to model the quality of red and white vinho verde wines based on their physicochemical properties. (The dataset includes 1599 samples of wine)
  • UCI - Dataset: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/wine+quality
  • Set Characteristics: Multivariate
  • Number of Instances: 4898
  • Number of Attributes: 12

[Data Cleaning and Preprocessing]

  • Removing unnecessary columns and converting it to int datatype
  • Relplace missing value

[Exploratory Data Analysis]

  • Hypothesis Analysis
  • Creating scatter plot, histogram of the dataset
  • Analyzing correlations,

[Model Training and Evaluation]

  • Splitting the dataset into training and testing sets
  • Training different ML models (LR,DT, LightGBM, RF)
  • Making predictions on the testing set and evaluating each model's performance by RMSE

[Conclusion]

  • Model Evaluation

1. Data Cleaning and Preprocessing¶

This code reads two wine datasets, one containing information about red wines and another containing information about white wines. A new column 'type' is added to each dataset to identify the type of wine. Then, both datasets are concatenated into a single dataset called 'wine'. Thre is no NaN.

Hypothesis Testing

  • H0: There is no difference between the type of wine and quality.
  • H1: There is a difference between the type of wine and quality.
In [ ]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

red_wine = wine[wine['type'] == 'red']['quality']
white_wine = wine[wine['type'] == 'white']['quality']

t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(red_wine, white_wine, equal_var=False)
print("t-statistic:", t_stat)
print("p-value:", p_val)

t-statistic: -10.149363059143164
p-value: 8.168348870049682e-24

Insight: Based on the t-statistic of -10.15 and the very low p-value of 8.17e-24, we can reject the null hypothesis. This means that there is a significant difference in the quality ratings of red and white wines.

Insights:

  • There is a moderate positive correlation between the fixed acidity and citric acid (0.32), while there is a moderate negative correlation between the pH and fixed acidity (-0.25).
  • The total sulfur dioxide and free sulfur dioxide attributes are highly positively correlated (0.72), indicating that they are measuring similar aspects of the wine.
  • The alcohol attribute has the highest positive correlation with the quality (0.44), this means that wines with higher alcohol content tend to have higher quality ratings.
  • The volatile acidity attribute has the highest negative correlation with the quality (-0.27), this means that wines with higher volatile acidity tend to have lower quality ratings.

PairGrid: This code generates a random sample of 200 red and white wines from the original wine dataset, and then creates a pair plot (PairGrid) of the variables 'quality', 'alcohol', 'residual sugar', and 'type' with hue set to 'type' (red or white).

  • The diagonal plot shows a histogram of each variable, while the off-diagonal shows a scatter plot of each combination of variables.
  • The plot visualize the relationships between the variables and their distributions for red and white wines.

3. ML Modeling (Linear Regression, Decision Tree Regressor, LightGBM, Random Forest)¶

The code performs several steps to evaluate different models' performance in predicting the quality of wine. It first splits the dataset into training and testing sets. Then, it builds four regression models, including linear regression, decision tree regressor, lightGBM, and random forest. Finally, it evaluates each model's performance using mean squared error as the metric.

Import ML Libraries and Split Train & Test Model

In [ ]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
import lightgbm as lgb
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
In [ ]:
X = wine.drop(['quality','type'], axis=1)
y = wine['quality']
In [ ]:
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X,y, test_size =0.3, random_state = 100)

fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(10, 8))

models = [('Linear Regression', y_pred_lr, lr_rmse), 
          ('Decision Tree Regression', y_pred_dt, dt_rmse), 
          ('LightGBM', y_pred_lgbm, lgbm_rmse), 
          ('Random Forest Regression', y_pred_rf, rf_rmse)]

for i, model in enumerate(models):
    ax = axs[i]
    ax.scatter(y_test, model[1], alpha=0.5, label=f'{model[0]}, RMSE={model[2]:.3f}')
    ax.plot([3,9],[3,9], color='red')
    ax.set_xlabel('Actual Quality')
    ax.set_ylabel('Predicted Quality')
    ax.legend()

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

4. Conclusion:¶

Based on the root mean squared error (RMSE) values, it seems that Random Forest Regression has the lowest error among the models you have trained with an RMSE of 0.6. The LightGBM Regression model also has a relatively low RMSE of 0.644. Linear Regression and Decision Tree Regression models have higher RMSE values of 0.728 and 0.873, respectively. Therefore, Random Forest Regression seems to be the best model for the given dataset based on the evaluation metric RMSE.
